<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>21854</anchor> <rss>sterling-angiuli-gratzer-2019-hott.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>sterling-angiuli-gratzer-2019-hott</addr>  <route>sterling-angiuli-gratzer-2019-hott.xml</route> <date><year>2019</year>  </date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author><author><link href="carloangiuli.xml" type="local" carloangiuli="addr">Carlo Angiuli</link></author><author><link href="danielgratzer.xml" type="local" danielgratzer="addr">Daniel Gratzer</link></author> </authors> <title>Cubical exact equality and categorical gluing</title> <meta name="slides">slides/sterling-angiuli-gratzer-2019-hott.pdf</meta><meta name="venue">International Conference on Homotopy Type Theory, 2019</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We contribute XTT, a cubical reconstruction of Observational Type Theory which extends intensional type theory with a dependent equality type that enjoys function extensionality and judgmental unicity of identity proofs. XTT employs a variant of the Cartesian cubical Kan operations satisfying regularity (i.e., transport in constant type families is judgmentally constant), allowing its equality type to model Martin-Lof’s identity type judgmentally. We prove canonicity for the initial model of XTT (i.e., any closed term of boolean type is equal to either true or false) using a novel cubical extension (independently proposed by <link href="steveawodey.xml" type="local" addr="steveawodey" title="Steve Awodey">Awodey</link>) of the categorical gluing technique inspired by <link href="thierrycoquand.xml" type="local" addr="thierrycoquand" title="Thierry Coquand">Coquand</link> and <link href="mikeshulman.xml" type="local" addr="mikeshulman" title="Mike Shulman">Shulman</link>, in which we glue the fundamental fibration of a category of augmented Cartesian cubical sets along a cubical nerve. We conjecture that our methods will extend to open terms, allowing us to establish normalization and decidability of the typing relation.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>21855</anchor> <rss>mikeshulman.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Person</taxon> <addr>mikeshulman</addr>  <route>mikeshulman.xml</route>   <title>Mike Shulman</title> <meta name="external">https://home.sandiego.edu/~shulman/</meta><meta name="position">Associate Professor</meta><meta name="institution">University of San Diego</meta><meta name="orcid">0000-0002-9948-6682</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter>
  
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
  
    
    
  
